  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Land Subsidence Vietnam</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Land subsidence is threatening the Mekong Delta. Its relations with other phenomena like sea level rise, loss of sediment in the river and overexploitation of groundwater resources are complex and the impacts are often additive to each other. Yet, land subsidence is BIG. And it does not feature prominently in the Mekong Delta Plan and Resolution 120. The Netherlands and Germany have a legacy of studying and working on land subsidence in the delta. The aim of the consultancy is threefold: first, to deepen our understand of land subsidence and its root causes; second to recommend policies to mitigate land subsidence and adapt to it; third to identify business opportunities (particularly for the Dutch sector) and identify improvements in the incentive structure for private companies to act upon land subsidence. The results of the consultancy are crucial to develop a sustainable  strategy for urban planning of HCMC. For that process another consultancy is contemplated. The second consultancy requires the results of the first one to define the scope and focus. The results will also help Dutch companies (both water users and consultancy firms) to introduce new technology, to plan financial investment and to benefit from arising demand for knowledge on land subsidence / groundwater use.</narrative>
  </description>
